observations.conclusion:
The difference indicated on the mark appears at the edge next to an area of smearing, which presumably has created the appearance of a bifurcation. I'm happy this can be explained.

My previous comments at analysis about the uncertainty of where primary ridges change to incipient ridges is borne out. There a few places where the features indicated are slightly out of sync but I haven't highlighted these as differences as it's obvious why they're out.

3. Degree of similarity - 5

The print has some distortion at the top of the print due to the way it has been rolled causing some characteristics to be further to the left than in the mark and also there is missing detail in the print that is present in the mark.
Some of the incipient ridges are not appearing exactly same in the mark and print which was as expected so some of the minutia placement might be off for the incipient ridges.
One minutia near the core (pairing point 17) I accidentally deleted then replaced so it came up yellow but I had it in my original analysis.

(C) Degree of Similarity = 5
(E) Degree of Support = 5

Degree of Similarity - 5
Although the incipient ridges make this mark look like there are more differences than there actually are in the marking up, there are little or no differences visible. The main difference on the LHS is most likely caused by the swipe through the mark. The differences near the core are caused by the uncertainty surrounding the incipient ridges. Top RHS not visible for comparison. 
Degree of support - 5

Extensive volume of incipient detail present making this mark extremely challenging to mark up. The accurate plotting of explainable differences became overwhelming and I eventually limited my plotting up to strong 2nd Level characteristics. 

Level of similarity: 5 (Although incipient detail greatly increases the level of explainable difference).

Level of support: 5

Degree of similarity: Total similarity
Degree of support: Strong support for identification

Pairing numbers went in to error and was unable to pair 63 in the unknown impression then 64 - 66 were omitted. 
Any differences noted are due to deposition pressure and, in turn, the presence of incipients.
